comments about results: Proliferation and migration were comparable across media, though CS10 reached confluency faster.

all ingredients in cryoprotective soluti: CryoStor CS10 (10% DMSO, serum-free), 2:1 DMEM/HAM F12, 10% FBS, 4 mM L-glutamine, 50 μg/mL penicillin-streptomycin, 5 μg/mL insulin, 0.4 μg/mL hydrocortisone, 0.18 mM adenine, 8.1 μg/mL cholera toxin, 2 nM triiodothyronine, 10 ng/mL EGF
cooling rate: Slow rate-controlled cooling using isopropanol freezing container (Mr. Frosty) to -20°C for 24h, then liquid nitrogen
recovery: Maintained clonogenic capacity (CFE 16.4% ± 0.9% clonogenic, 3.2% ± 0.8% abortive), proliferative capacity (CCD 47 ± 3.3 doublings), and differentiation (p63α 20.1% ± 11.4% at P3, 22.9% ± 21.7% at P5; K19 68.9% ± 10.1% at P3, 64.0% ± 12.5% at P5)
comments about method: Conjunctival cells from 3 cadaveric donors (36–79 years) isolated by trypsin/EDTA, cultured on 3T3-J2 feeder layer, cryopreserved in 0.5 mL CryoStor CS10 (10% DMSO) with culture medium, slow cooling (Mr. Frosty) to -20°C for 24h then liquid nitrogen for 30 days; viability by trypan blue, quality tests (CFE, CCD, immunohistochemistry) over 6 passages; statistical analysis with two-tailed t-test (p<0.05, SPSS v24)
comments about results: Viability 79.9% ± 7.0%, higher than glycerol (p=0.001); maintained proliferative (CCD 47 ± 3.3), clonogenic (CFE 16.4% ± 0.9%), and differentiation capacity (p63α, K19 unchanged, p≥0.05)
